{
  "answer": "**Ghalib's ghazal \"Dil-e-naadaan tujhe hua kya hai\" (Diwan-e-Ghalib, ghazal 36)** opens by directly addressing the \"foolish heart\" (*dil-e-nā-dāān*, translated as \"my foolish heart\").[^1]\n\nThe opening couplet asks it two linked questions:  \n*What's happened to you (or what's led you to this state/sway)?*  \n*And what, ultimately, is the remedy (*dawa*) for this deep pain?*[^2]\n\nThe original Urdu (first couplet):  \nدلِ ناداں تجھے ہوا کیا ہے  \nآخر اس درد کی دوا کیا ہے  \n\nThis sets the tone for the ghazal, which repeatedly questions the nature of love's torment, the beloved's indifference, creation itself, and divine mystery—all ending in the refrain *kyā hai* (\"what is it?\").[^3]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/36-dil-e-naadaan-tujhe-hua-kya-hai/translation/#p-414b38).\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [passage](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/36-dil-e-naadaan-tujhe-hua-kya-hai/translation/#p-414b38).\n\n[^3]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [chapter](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/36-dil-e-naadaan-tujhe-hua-kya-hai/translation/).",
